<h2 class="mt-5 mb-3 text-3xl leading-8 font-extrabold font-header tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-2xl">1) The Problem:</h2>
<p>Many Substack writers, such as <a href="https://www.citeit.net/demo/substack/www.racket.news/p/who-blew-up-the-nord-stream-pipelines/">Matt Taibbi and Matt Orfalea</a>, stretch the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overton_window">Overton Window</a> (what is considered <strong>politically acceptable to say</strong>) <a href="#footnote-1-3424" id="note-1-3424" rel="footnote">1</a>
Unfortunately, while <strong>Racket News&rsquo;s</strong> existing subscribers are receptive to it, <strong>when it is shared with others, it meets resistance</strong> that prevents Substack outlets like <strong>Racket News from broadening their subscriber base</strong>. <a href="#footnote-2-3424" id="note-2-3424" rel="footnote">2</a>
I&rsquo;ve developed the <a href="https://www.citeit.net/">CiteIt Citation App</a> to <strong>address 3 stumbling blocks</strong> faced by Substack writers:</p>
<ol class="num" />
  <li><strong>Skeptics</strong> suspect that quotes have been <strong>taken out of context</strong>, <a href="#footnote-3-3424" id="note-3-3424" rel="footnote">3</a> while also being ..</li>
  <li><strong>too</strong> <strong>busy</strong> and <strong>dismissive</strong> to investigate whether their suspicions or a the writer&rsquo;s <strong>negative reputation</strong> are warranted.<a href="#footnote-4-3424" id="note-4-3424" rel="footnote">4</a> <a href="#footnote-5-3424" id="note-5-3424" rel="footnote">5</a></li>
  <li><strong>Gatekeepers for the establishment&nbsp;</strong> nitpick,<a href="#footnote-6-3424" id="note-6-3424" rel="footnote">6</a> censor, shadow-ban, throttle, or even threaten perjury charges when independent writers challenge establishment interests or perspectives. <a href="#footnote-7-3424" id="note-7-3424" rel="footnote">7</a>
   <ul class="disc">
      <li>Adding to these stumbling blocks, <strong>partisan allies react</strong> to the arguments of partisan gatekeepers, arguing <q cite="https://youtu.be/DWKgHOMAH7w?t=1155" data-citeit-citing-url="https://pages.citeit.net/2023/07/19/how-substack-writers-can-address-the-crisis-of-trust/">they pretend that they&rsquo;re being censored when in reality they just don&rsquo;t want editors but they need them</q></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>


<h2 class="mt-7 mb-3 text-3xl leading-8 font-extrabold font-header tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-2xl">2) How CiteIt Works:</h2>
<p>Let&rsquo;s look at an example article &mdash; <a href="https://www.citeit.net/demo/substack/www.racket.news/p/who-blew-up-the-nord-stream-pipelines/">Matt Taibbi&rsquo;s Nord Stream article</a> &mdash; containing what I call &ldquo;<strong>naked quotations</strong>&rdquo; &mdash; that is quotations that have no surrounding context.<a href="#footnote-8-3424" id="note-8-3424" rel="footnote">8</a>.&nbsp; These type of quotations are regarded with suspicion by <strong>non-aligned non-subscribers</strong>.</p>
<p>Now, lets see the same article, only with the <strong>writer using CiteIt to:</strong></p>
<ul class="disc">
    <li><strong>link to their sources</strong>, <a href="#footnote-9-3424" id="note-9-3424" rel="footnote">9</a></li>
    <li><strong>lookup the context, and </strong><a href="#footnote-10-3424" id="note-10-3424" rel="footnote">10</a></li>
    <li><strong>display it to the reader </strong>(see: right-side popup dialog: &ldquo;<strong>Quote Context by CiteIt.net</strong>&ldquo;):</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>CiteIt Looks up Linked quotations:</strong></p>
<div id="attachment_3475" style="width: 685px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.citeit.net/demo/substack/www.racket.news/p/who-blew-up-the-nord-stream-pipelines/"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-3475" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-3475" src="https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-there-will-no-longer-be-1024x819.png" alt="Screenshot: CiteIt used with Nord Stream Bombing quote" width="675" height="540" srcset="https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-there-will-no-longer-be-1024x819.png 1024w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-there-will-no-longer-be-300x240.png 300w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-there-will-no-longer-be-768x615.png 768w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-there-will-no-longer-be.png 1196w" sizes="(max-width: 675px) 100vw, 675px"></a><p id="caption-attachment-3475" class="wp-caption-text"><br><strong>Video</strong> and <strong>Transcript</strong> have been looked up from link: (<strong>right side popup</strong>: &ldquo;Quote Context by CiteIt.net&rdquo;)</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Using the current <a href="https://www.citeit.net/try/">WordPress implementation </a>of CiteIt, the plugin adds <strong>2 custom</strong> <strong>buttons to the editor.</strong></p>
<p>The writers click on the &ldquo;<strong>CiteIt inline popup button&rdquo;</strong>, and <strong>paste in the source URL </strong>just like a traditional editor &ldquo;link&rdquo; button. <a href="#footnote-11-3424" id="note-11-3424" rel="footnote">11</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Add 2 CiteIt buttons to Editor:</strong></p>
<div id="attachment_3476" style="width: 685px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.citeit.net/#try"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-3476" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-3476" src="https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-We-will-bring-an-end-to-it.png" alt='The writer enters the link URL after they click the "CiteIt Inline Popup" button' width="675" height="424" srcset="https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-We-will-bring-an-end-to-it.png 1013w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-We-will-bring-an-end-to-it-300x188.png 300w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-We-will-bring-an-end-to-it-768x482.png 768w, https://pages.citeit.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CiteIt-Screenshot-We-will-bring-an-end-to-it-540x340.png 540w" sizes="(max-width: 675px) 100vw, 675px"></a><p id="caption-attachment-3476" class="wp-caption-text">The Writer <strong>enters the link URL</strong> after they select the quote and click the &ldquo;<strong>CiteIt inline popup</strong>&rdquo; <strong>button</strong></p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Then when the article is published, the CiteIt plugin <strong>locates all the cited web sources</strong> and YouTube video transcripts.<a href="#footnote-12-3424" id="note-12-3424" rel="footnote">12</a><a href="#footnote-13-3424" id="note-13-3424" rel="footnote">13</a></p>
<p>The CiteIt webservice then <strong>finds the 500 characters of context</strong> before and after the quote and saves that information <strong>to display when the reader requests it.</strong></p>
<p>Contextual citations are about <strong>more than policing cherry-picked quotes</strong> or disinformation.&nbsp; Contextual Citations give readers a <strong>better understanding of the source</strong>.&nbsp; This can clearly be seen when readers are able to <strong>dive into the context</strong> surrounding quotes like <q cite="https://youtu.be/MX_v0zxM23Q?t=125" data-citeit-citing-url="https://pages.citeit.net/2023/07/19/how-substack-writers-can-address-the-crisis-of-trust/">The only thing we have to fear is &ldquo;fear itself</q>&ldquo;.</p>


<h2 class="mt-7 mb-3 text-3xl leading-8 font-extrabold font-header tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-2xl">3) What Success Would Look Like:</h2>
<p>I want Substack to <strong>establish a reputation for a higher standard of transparency and trust in media</strong>&nbsp;by:</p>
<ul class="disc">
    <li><strong>better informing</strong> their readers, <a href="#footnote-14-3424" id="note-14-3424" rel="footnote">14</a></li>
    <li>build <strong>trust</strong>, and&nbsp; <a href="#footnote-15-3424" id="note-15-3424" rel="footnote">15</a></li>
    <li>helping to <strong>differentiate Substack</strong> from platforms like Twitter and Threads,</li>
    <li><strong>defending reputations</strong> from gatekeepers and partisans. <a href="#footnote-16-3424" id="note-16-3424" rel="footnote">16</a></li>
</ul>
<p>If I aim higher, I will know we&rsquo;ve been <strong>maximally successful</strong> when I hear the concept of <strong>contextual citations </strong>discussed in general conversation<strong>:</strong><a href="#footnote-17-3424" id="note-17-3424" rel="footnote">17</a></p>
<ul>
    <li>associated with Substack, trust, innovation, and independent writers, <a href="#footnote-18-3424" id="note-18-3424" rel="footnote">18</a></li>
    <li>described as a solution to &ldquo;<strong>naked quotations</strong>&ldquo;<a href="#footnote-19-3424" id="note-19-3424" rel="footnote">19</a><a href="#footnote-20-3424" id="note-20-3424" rel="footnote">20</a>, and</li>
    <li>used as a <strong>critique of establishment</strong> <strong>media</strong> that does not provide <strong>contextual transparency</strong>.<a href="#footnote-21-3424" id="note-21-3424" rel="footnote">21</a></li>
</ul>

