<h3 class="mt-7 mb-3 text-3xl leading-8 font-extrabold font-header tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-2xl">Footnotes:</h3>

<div class="footnotes"><hr /><ol><li id="footnote-1-3424" class="footnote"><p>In a world that is increasingly partisan and censorious.<a href="#note-1-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-1.footnote--><li id="footnote-2-3424" class="footnote"><p>By resistance I include <strong>resistance from non-subscribers</strong> who may experience cognitive dissonance with the work, resistance in the form of being <strong>too busy or dismissive to investigate</strong> the claims, and <strong>resistance from gatekeepers</strong>.<a href="#note-2-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-2.footnote--><li id="footnote-3-3424" class="footnote"><p>Sometimes <strong>skepticism</strong> is a <strong>rationalization</strong> when an article is shared with people who are <strong>non-aligned politically</strong>.&nbsp; The non-subscriber may face <strong>cognitive dissonance</strong> when their political views don&rsquo;t align with a work.<a href="#note-3-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-3.footnote--><li id="footnote-4-3424" class="footnote"><p>A friend of mine who I shared the <a href="https://www.citeit.net/demo/substack/www.racket.news/p/who-blew-up-the-nord-stream-pipelines/">Nord Stream article</a> with, initially balked for partisan reasons because he had been told that Matt Taibbi was &ldquo;right-wing&rdquo; for associating with Elon Musk.<a href="#note-4-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-4.footnote--><li id="footnote-5-3424" class="footnote"><p><strong>I do not think CiteIt is a panacea</strong>, but it can be <strong>emphasized that the writer is referencing sources</strong> and has <strong>made it easy for readers to inspect them</strong>. <a href="#note-5-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-5.footnote--><li id="footnote-6-3424" class="footnote"><p>See <a href="https://youtu.be/a597e6Wv_xg">Mehdi Hassan&rsquo;s &ldquo;nitpicking&rdquo;</a>, which had the effect of <strong>gatekeeping for the &ldquo;CIC&rdquo; (Censorship Industrial Complex)</strong> over the <strong>Twitter Files</strong><a href="#note-6-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-6.footnote--><li id="footnote-7-3424" class="footnote"><p>In a hearing on the &ldquo;Weaponization of the Federal Government,&rdquo; <a href="https://youtu.be/c7VEbbwnI-4">Stacey Plaskett</a>, Virgin Island Democratic Delegate <strong>threatened Matt Taibbi</strong> with up to <strong>5 years in prison</strong> for <strong>&ldquo;perjury.&rdquo;</strong><a href="#note-7-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-7.footnote--><li id="footnote-8-3424" class="footnote"><p>I really like <strong>Matt Orfalea&rsquo;s video</strong>, which I recall preceded the article, but this video format is <strong>designed to tell a story</strong> and can&rsquo;t provide enough context to satisfy skeptics. <a href="https://pages.citeit.net/2023/04/13/usability-testing-citeit-first-series/">When I did a usability test</a> of my demo article, I found that a significant number of readers <strong>skipped the video and went straight to the article</strong>.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s why my demo <strong>integrated contextual video with the article</strong>.&nbsp; I know at this point, <strong>readers haven&rsquo;t been introduced to CiteIt</strong>, so they don&rsquo;t know what to expect, but <strong>my hope is that this becomes conventional</strong> for readers..<a href="#note-8-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-8.footnote--><li id="footnote-9-3424" class="footnote"><p>The WordPress implementation add a special button that writers use to link to their source<a href="#note-9-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-9.footnote--><li id="footnote-10-3424" class="footnote"><p>When an article is published, CiteIt follows the link and looks up the source&rsquo;s context<a href="#note-10-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-10.footnote--><li id="footnote-11-3424" class="footnote"><p>My goal is to make it <strong>as easy to create a contextual link</strong> as it is to create a standard link.<a href="#note-11-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-11.footnote--><li id="footnote-12-3424" class="footnote"><p>To be sure, it is currently possible to embed video in articles, but this <strong>takes up space</strong> and <strong>breaks up the flow of the article</strong>.&nbsp; The other option is to create a link that sends the reader to a new page.&nbsp; <strong>CiteIt keeps the reader within the article</strong> and <strong>automates</strong> the process of <strong>looking up and displaying the context</strong>.<a href="#note-12-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-12.footnote--><li id="footnote-13-3424" class="footnote"><p>You can see how contextual YouTube citations are <strong>implemented in HTML</strong> on the <a href="https://www.citeit.net/#how">homepage</a>.<a href="#note-13-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-13.footnote--><li id="footnote-14-3424" class="footnote"><p>Quotes, such as the FDR quote (above) about &ldquo;fear itself&rdquo; can <strong>convey much more information</strong> to the reader <strong>when context is added</strong>, particularly when videos are used.<a href="#note-14-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-14.footnote--><li id="footnote-15-3424" class="footnote"><p>Readers who can easily verify quotes are more like to understand and trust a writer that makes themselves more accountable to inspection.<a href="#note-15-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-15.footnote--><li id="footnote-16-3424" class="footnote"><p>I would anticipate that Substack writers could use CiteIt&rsquo;s contextual citations as a <strong>marketing point</strong> that <strong>demonstrates</strong> <strong>the higher standard of transparency</strong> that they employ, which the mainstream press will have a hard time matching.<a href="#note-16-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-16.footnote--><li id="footnote-17-3424" class="footnote"><p>I&rsquo;m using this term of &ldquo;<strong>contextual citations</strong>&rdquo; as a generic way to describe citations that show readers the context of a text, audio, or video, that <strong>doesn&rsquo;t require the reader to follow a link</strong> in which they <strong>leave the original work</strong>.<a href="#note-17-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-17.footnote--><li id="footnote-18-3424" class="footnote"><p>I hope readers recognize that <strong>innovation</strong> is coming via Substack and independent writers.&nbsp; Make sure to claim credit for it! <a href="#note-18-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-18.footnote--><li id="footnote-19-3424" class="footnote"><p>Or whatever you <strong>want to name the concept</strong> of quotes that do not show their context<a href="#note-19-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-19.footnote--><li id="footnote-20-3424" class="footnote"><p>The difference between a &ldquo;<strong>cherry picked</strong>&rdquo; quotation and a &ldquo;naked quote is that a <strong>cherry-picked quote is deliberately</strong> selected to be misrepresentative, while a &ldquo;<strong>naked quotation</strong>&rdquo; is a quotation that does not contain context.&nbsp; Naked quotations need not be deceptive. Rather they are <strong>opaque</strong> to the reader<a href="#note-20-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-20.footnote--><li id="footnote-21-3424" class="footnote"><p>Ideally, I would want to hear the concept of <strong>contextual citations</strong> associated with the <strong>entire Substack platform</strong>: including notes, podcasts, and video <a href="#note-21-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-21.footnote--><li id="footnote-22-3424" class="footnote"><p> I saved a copy of a <a href="https://www.citeit.net/assets/images/CiteIt-Substack-draft-next-steps.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Slide that outlines Proposed Next Steps</a> <a href="#note-22-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-22.footnote--><li id="footnote-23-3424" class="footnote"><p>CiteIt could help <strong>differentiate Substack Notes</strong> from <a href="https://twitter.com/home">Twittter</a> and <a href="https://about.instagram.com/blog/announcements/threads-instagram-text-feature">Threads</a> <a href="#note-23-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-23.footnote--><li id="footnote-24-3424" class="footnote"><p>CiteIt could make it easy for anyone on Substack to <strong>embed a contextual quote</strong> of a <strong>podcast</strong> or <strong>video</strong> <a href="#note-24-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-24.footnote--><li id="footnote-25-3424" class="footnote"><p>Adding CiteIt support for podcasts would require <strong>adding transcription support</strong>.<a href="#note-25-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-25.footnote--><li id="footnote-26-3424" class="footnote"><p>It appears that <a href="https://api.substack.com/feed/podcast/8079/private/7763ea6c-0ece-4290-a191-f25973d0be4e.rss">Substack podcasts have RSS Summaries, but are not completely transcribed</a>. (<a href="https://www.historicly.net/p/the-casualties-of-war-part-1-with#details">Historic.ly</a>)<br>
<a href="#note-26-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-26.footnote--><li id="footnote-27-3424" class="footnote"><p><strong>CiteIt currently supports YouTube</strong>, but could be expanded to support Substack Video, Vimeo, and other formats if it added <strong>transcription support</strong>.<a href="#note-27-3424" class="footnote-return">&#8617;</a></p></li><!--/#footnote-27.footnote--></ol></div><!--/#footnotes--><!--<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
